Sure, everyone has played with plasma balls before, but that doesn't make them any less cool.  This is Mary having a shocking time.

In recent years, the Edinburgh Fringe has been enriched by the presence of a number of groups from South Korea. They have been a great source of photographs for me.

This group were making a return visit, having previously been here for the 2006 Fringe (when I photographed their show). They performed a traditional Korean love story called 'Choon-Hyang', where all the roles were played by child actors.
Night falling on Waverly station and the Balmoral Hotel in Edinburgh (Scotland).

An exclusive shot from last year's Edinburgh Fringe where we were honoured with a visit from Lord Xenu, the ruler of the Galactic Confederacy. As you will know, according to Scientology beliefs, it was Xenu who brought billions of frozen people to Earth 75 million years ago, stacked them around volcanoes and blew them up with hydrogen bombs, creating swarms of disembodied alien souls known as Body Thetans. This was Lord Xenu's first visit to the Edinburgh Fringe, where he starred in: "Xenu is loose! Cower puny humans as the Dark Prince of the Galactic Federation rains Atomic Death once more upon your pitiful planet - The Musical', which was apparently the longest title of any show ever to appear at the Edinburgh Fringe. One can only assume he got decent reviews...since we seem to have been spared the atomic death...phew! You can see some other pics I took of Lord Xenu at these locations: Cower Puny Humans! If I Ruled the World?

I have to admit that, in its place, I like grafitti. The proper stuff. Not just a tagged name, or 'For sex phone....'.

During the festival, Edinburgh's Chambers Street turns into a glorified coach park. Most of those buses will have taken people to see the dreaded tattoo up at the Castle.

The real Gilded Balloon was destroyed in the awful fire that gutted a historic block in the centre of Edinburgh a few years ago, but the organisers have risen from the ashes, creating new Gilded Balloons in various places. This building was Edinburgh University Students' Union in my day, and in more recent years it's housed the Fringe Club. I've sort of lost track of its various identities, but this year it seems to have become the Gilded Balloon. I have no idea what the tourists know it as, of course!

Finally, a Thursday Utata walk.  Yay!

I went all botanical and being silly with aperture settings.  Hmm what if I do f1.8 with 3000 shutter speed???? I also took along my T90 film SLR. 

I mercilessly stalked a crow, much to the amusement of two Polish grannies sat on a bench behind me. I flitted around a pretty butterfly and the butterfly won. I drooled over ornamental bark in dappled sunlight and the dapples were both under and over-exposed - howzat for technique! You'll notice that none of those shots made it here, surprise surprise.

But the main thing was that I enjoyed myself, even if I did stay out too long and am now sore sore sore sore.

The North Merchiston Cemetary, in Edinburgh, is a very spooky place. Left unmaintained for a while before it was taken over by Edinburgh City Council, it's still, ironically enough, very much a "ghost graveyard", with broken tombs buried under ivy and invaded by bluebells and whild Garlic. The City Council is slowly repairing the damages, so it might lose its eery psookiness in the months to come.

O.K. a little more about Scotlands national emblem The Thistle.
The story goes that Edinburgh Castle Garrison were being surrreptitiously advanced upon by the dreaded English when a footsoldier stepped on a thistle and cried out in pain which alerted the castle guard and the Auld enemy were defeated as a result
The Most Ancient and Most Noble Order of the Thistle is an order of chivalry associated with Scotland. The current version of the Order was founded in 1687 by King James VII of Scotland (also known as James II of England) who asserted that he was reviving an earlier Order. The Order consists of the Sovereign and sixteen Knights and Ladies, as well as certain "extra" knights (members of the British Royal Family and foreign monarchs). The Sovereign alone grants membership of the Order; he or she is not advised by the Government, as occurs with most other Orders. The sixteen members are required to be Scottish-born, though not the "extra" knights and ladies.

The Order's primary emblem is the thistle, the national flower of Scotland. The motto is Nemo me impune lacessit (Latin for "No one provokes me with impunity") or to put it in laymens terms "no one screws with me and gets away with it.
